{"parse":{"title":"Pangat","pageid":49925199,"revid":853116959,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla,_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla%2C_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg/220px-Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla%2C_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"293\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla%2C_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg/330px-Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla%2C_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla%2C_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg/440px-Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla%2C_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3000\" data-file-height=\"4000\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pangat_offered_at_Vishnu_temple_in_Sajla,_Himachal_Pradesh.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Pangat offered at Vishnu temple in Sajla, <a href=\"/wiki/Himachal_Pradesh\" title=\"Himachal Pradesh\">Himachal Pradesh</a></div></div></div>\n<p><b>Pangat</b> is a word derived from the <a href=\"/wiki/Sanskrit\" title=\"Sanskrit\">Sanskrit</a> word <i>pankti</i> (<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://dsalsrv02.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/app/macdonell_query.py?qs=%E0%A4%AA%E0%A4%99%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%95%E0%A5%8D%E0%A4%A4%E0%A4%BF&amp;searchhws=yes\">\u092a\u0919\u094d\u0915\u094d\u0924\u093f</a>) that means a line, a row, or a group. It is a synonym for <i>Guru Ka Langar</i>. In a Pangat, food is served by volunteers (Sevadars) to people of all religions who sit together to eat.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Pangat is about eating food while sitting in rows with no discrimination on the basis of <a href=\"/wiki/Caste\" title=\"Caste\">caste</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Creed\" title=\"Creed\">creed</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Religion\" title=\"Religion\">religion</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> According to the beliefs of Sikhism, nobody sleeps without eating, nor should anybody die of hunger.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pangat&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Pangat and Sangat came together from the time of <a href=\"/wiki/Guru_Nanak\" title=\"Guru Nanak\">Guru Nanak Dev Ji</a>, the first Guru of <a href=\"/wiki/Sikh\" title=\"Sikh\">Sikhism</a>. Nanak's father gave him money for trade that he spent on feeding hungry <a href=\"/wiki/Sadhu\" title=\"Sadhu\">Sadhus</a>. He named this that <i>True Transaction</i> (Sacha Sauda). Where there is Sangat, there is always a Langar (food service).<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> According to Sikh principles all people (Sangat) who sit in pangat share food on equal basis. \n</p><p>In the history of Sikhism, when <a href=\"/wiki/Akbar\" title=\"Akbar\">Emperor Akbar</a> and the King of Haripur went to meet Guru Amar Das Ji, the third Guru of Sikhism. They both had to eat Langar in the pangat before meeting the Guru.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Pangat&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.sikhiwiki.org/index.php/Pangat\">\"Pangat - SikhiWiki, free Sikh encyclopedia\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Pangat+-+SikhiWiki%2C+free+Sikh+encyclopedia.&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.sikhiwiki.org%2Findex.php%2FPangat&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APangat\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.allaboutsikhs.com/sikh-institutions/sangat-and-pangat\">\"Sangat and Pangat - Sikh Institutions - Gateway to Sikhism\"</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.btitle=Sangat+and+Pangat+-+Sikh+Institutions+-+Gateway+to+Sikhism&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.allaboutsikhs.com%2Fsikh-institutions%2Fsangat-and-pangat&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3APangat\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://sikhism.about.com/od/sikhdiningtradition/tp/All-About-Langar.htm\">\"All About Sacred Langar and the Guru's Free Kitchen\"</a>.</cite><spa